1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:06,900
Let's first talk about what is GPT and get a very high level overview of how it works.

2

00:00:06,900  -->  00:00:12,200
GPT stands for generative, pretrained transformers.

3

00:00:12,200  -->  00:00:17,220
Generative means that this model can generate text.

4

00:00:17,220  -->  00:00:23,160
Pretrained means that it was trained on large amounts of data.

5

00:00:23,270  -->  00:00:30,510
Transformers is a name of a network architecture that was used to create the GPT model.

6

00:00:30,510  -->  00:00:32,670
Network architecture refers to

7

00:00:32,670  -->  00:00:37,130
how different blocks of a neural network are arranged together.

8

00:00:37,130  -->  00:00:39,305
You should be already familiar with

9

00:00:39,305  -->  00:00:43,670
feedforward networks and convolutional networks

10

00:00:43,670  -->  00:00:46,470
that are commonly used for image classification.

11

00:00:46,470  -->  00:00:51,110
Transformers is another more recently developed network architecture

12

00:00:51,110  -->  00:00:53,610
that was created for processing text.

13

00:00:53,610  -->  00:00:58,605
For example, for tasks like translating from one language to another,

14

00:00:58,605  -->  00:01:00,640
or for text generation,

15

00:01:00,640  -->  00:01:03,660
as the core of transformers is the ability of

16

00:01:03,660  -->  00:01:07,980
a model to generate the next word given some input text.

17

00:01:07,980  -->  00:01:14,420
For example, I've provided input in a shocking turn of events to one of the GPT models,

18

00:01:14,420  -->  00:01:17,320
and it returned a single word it,

19

00:01:17,320  -->  00:01:23,180
which the model considers to be the best next word given this input sentence.

20

00:01:23,180  -->  00:01:25,600
If we add the next predicted word to

21

00:01:25,600  -->  00:01:30,400
the input phrase and pass this new phrase into the model again,

22

00:01:30,400  -->  00:01:33,075
it will provide another word.

23

00:01:33,075  -->  00:01:36,650
We can now add this word again to the input,

24

00:01:36,650  -->  00:01:40,310
and we can repeat this process again and again.

25

00:01:40,430  -->  00:01:43,610
It seems very limited at first,

26

00:01:43,610  -->  00:01:46,470
but if we repeat this enough times,

27

00:01:46,470  -->  00:01:48,870
we can get a meaningful output.

28

00:01:48,870  -->  00:01:52,730
For example, given the following input text,

29

00:01:52,730  -->  00:01:55,470
a model has generated this beginning of

30

00:01:55,470  -->  00:02:00,500
a fictional new story doing this one word at a time.

31

00:02:00,500  -->  00:02:03,250
To define some terminology,

32

00:02:03,250  -->  00:02:08,050
the input we provide to a model is also called a prompt,

33

00:02:08,050  -->  00:02:12,510
and we will use the words input and prompt interchangeably.

34

00:02:12,510  -->  00:02:15,330
It turns out that during their training,

35

00:02:15,330  -->  00:02:19,690
models can learn a lot of information about the real world.

36

00:02:19,690  -->  00:02:25,445
For example, if we give a model a prompt like the capital of Paris is,

37

00:02:25,445  -->  00:02:28,620
It will likely return Paris.

38

00:02:28,620  -->  00:02:31,720
To do it, it should have learned about cities,

39

00:02:31,720  -->  00:02:34,320
capitals, how to answer questions,

40

00:02:34,320  -->  00:02:35,860
and many other things.

41

00:02:35,860  -->  00:02:38,380
Given the large amount of training data,

42

00:02:38,380  -->  00:02:42,740
GPT models became very proficient in a variety of tasks.

43

00:02:42,740  -->  00:02:46,350
Even in tasks, they were not trained for specifically.

44

00:02:46,350  -->  00:02:52,920
For example, I gave a prompt to one of the GPT models to write a poem about transformers,

45

00:02:52,920  -->  00:02:56,200
and it returned this output.

46

00:02:56,260  -->  00:03:00,080
Or these models can generate code.

47

00:03:00,080  -->  00:03:02,000
Like in this example,

48

00:03:02,000  -->  00:03:07,540
where I've asked a model to write a function that calculates a Fibonacci number.

49

00:03:07,540  -->  00:03:12,180
Transformer models are not just limited to generating text.

50

00:03:12,180  -->  00:03:16,780
We can use transformers to convert text into audio,

51

00:03:16,780  -->  00:03:22,980
or we can generate images described by a particular prompt.

52

00:03:23,100  -->  00:03:31,060
The field of AI that allows to generate new data is called generative AI.

53

00:03:32,010  -->  00:03:37,010
There has been a proliferation of new generative AI models,

54

00:03:37,010  -->  00:03:41,110
and they are usually based on the transformer architecture.

55

00:03:41,110  -->  00:03:44,150
These models can generate images,

56

00:03:44,150  -->  00:03:47,570
text, audio, and videos.

57

00:03:48,120  -->  00:03:55,380
In this course, we will learn about so called large language models or LLMs, for short.

58

00:03:55,380  -->  00:03:59,650
These models were trained on massive amounts of data.

59

00:03:59,650  -->  00:04:03,160
Using these models, we can generate text,

60

00:04:03,160  -->  00:04:07,250
use them to answer questions, and so on.

61

00:04:07,360  -->  00:04:11,005
But how we can use these models?

62

00:04:11,005  -->  00:04:16,070
One way is to use a set of GPT models from OpenAI.

63

00:04:16,070  -->  00:04:18,580
These models can understand text,

64

00:04:18,580  -->  00:04:22,925
images, and voice, and reply to users questions.

65

00:04:22,925  -->  00:04:29,790
Alternatively, we can use Gemini models from Google that have similar capabilities.

66

00:04:29,790  -->  00:04:36,430
Another commonly used set of models are called stable diffusion from Stability AI.

67

00:04:36,430  -->  00:04:38,730
These models are very good at

68

00:04:38,730  -->  00:04:43,690
generating images given an input prompt describing an image.

69

00:04:43,690  -->  00:04:46,710
There are also some other popular open source

70

00:04:46,710  -->  00:04:50,905
LLMs that you can download and run on your computer.

71

00:04:50,905  -->  00:04:58,985
These include Llama models developed by Meta and Mistral models developed by Mistral AI.

72

00:04:58,985  -->  00:05:01,500
When we talk about a GPT model,

73

00:05:01,500  -->  00:05:04,445
we're not talking about a single model.

74

00:05:04,445  -->  00:05:09,720
OpenAI has trained a myriad of different models with different versions.

75

00:05:09,720  -->  00:05:13,020
Even a model with the same major version like

76

00:05:13,020  -->  00:05:16,900
GPT-4 has been updated and refined over time.

77

00:05:16,900  -->  00:05:24,480
There is refinements and improvements have their own names like GPT-4 Turbo or GPT-4o.

78

00:05:24,480  -->  00:05:28,920
When using OpenAI products like ChatGPT or their API,

79

00:05:28,920  -->  00:05:31,460
we can select the model version to use.

80

00:05:31,460  -->  00:05:34,040
Although some models like GPT-2 and

81

00:05:34,040  -->  00:05:38,800
GPT-3 have already been deprecated and are no longer available.

82

00:05:38,800  -->  00:05:43,660
Other companies have also produced many different versions of their models.

83

00:05:43,660  -->  00:05:47,090
For example, Meta has trained Llama 2 and

84

00:05:47,090  -->  00:05:52,180
Llama 3 and created different versions of Llama 3.
